00:01:49.050 --> 00:01:53.920
Signe Wilkinson and Ann Telnaes
have to the Library at a time

00:01:53.920 --> 00:01:57.760
when public attention and
debate over the significance

00:01:57.760 --> 00:02:00.270
of the <i>Charlie Hebdo</i>
tragedy and the role

00:02:00.270 --> 00:02:03.590
of free speech have
been reinvigorated.

00:02:03.590 --> 00:02:05.900
Causes, you might ask.

00:02:05.900 --> 00:02:08.660
"Doonesbury's" creator,
Gary Trudeau,

00:02:08.660 --> 00:02:11.270
recently commented
critically on the nature

00:02:11.270 --> 00:02:13.950
of the <i>Charlie Hebdo</i>
cartoonist's work,

00:02:13.950 --> 00:02:17.360
describing it as "punching down."

00:02:17.360 --> 00:02:19.460
Many of his peers disagreed,

00:02:19.460 --> 00:02:22.360
including our cartoonists
here today.

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:26.190
Also, when the PEN/Faulkner
Writers' Group recently decided

00:02:26.190 --> 00:02:29.040
to make an award to
<i>Charlie Hebdo Magazine </i>,

00:02:29.040 --> 00:02:31.260
five member writers
publicly declined

00:02:31.260 --> 00:02:35.200
to attend the group's
fundraising gala.

00:02:35.200 --> 00:02:39.100
So, against this unanticipated
backdrop,

00:02:39.100 --> 00:02:42.770 position:56%
we asked these two distinguished
cartoonists to share their responses

00:02:42.770 --> 00:02:45.850
to the tragic murders
of the five cartoonists

00:02:45.850 --> 00:02:52.390 position:56%
at <i>Charlie Hebdo Magazine </i>in
January of this year, their thoughts

00:02:52.390 --> 00:02:55.860
on free speech, other
cartoonists' related work,

00:02:55.860 --> 00:02:58.740
and their takes on
Trudeau's comments.

00:02:58.740 --> 00:03:03.260 position:56%
In addition to these very timely
concerns, we also asked them to show

00:03:03.260 --> 00:03:07.820
and discuss their own controversial
cartoons and cartoons relating

00:03:07.820 --> 00:03:11.420 position:56%
to women's issues and gender issues.

00:03:11.420 --> 00:03:14.590
Signe and Ann are among a
very small number of women

00:03:14.590 --> 00:03:19.230
who pursue political cartooning
as their main professional focus.

00:03:19.230 --> 00:03:22.900
Okay. I'm going to --

00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:29.750
-- Signe Wilkinson is
the Editorial Cartoonist

00:03:29.750 --> 00:03:31.510
for the <i>Philadelphia Daily News </i>--

00:03:31.510 --> 00:03:33.310 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: I'm on the left.

00:03:33.310 --> 00:03:37.660
[ Laughter ]

00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:41.320
&gt;&gt; Martha H. Kennedy: --
and she is also contributing

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:44.120
to the <i>Philadelphia
Enquirer </i>these days.

00:03:44.120 --> 00:03:48.520
In 1992 she became the first
woman to win the Pulitzer Prize

00:03:48.520 --> 00:03:50.310
for her political cartoons.

00:03:50.310 --> 00:03:51.870 position:56%
And this prize-winning group focused

00:03:51.870 --> 00:03:54.400
on human needs and
social conditions.

00:03:54.400 --> 00:03:57.630
She has received many other
prestigious awards including the

00:03:57.630 --> 00:04:03.670
Thomas Nast Award from the
Overseas Press Club in 1996, 2000,

00:04:03.670 --> 00:04:07.280
2006, and this year, too.

00:04:07.280 --> 00:04:11.100
She's also received the Robert F.
Kennedy Journalism Award in 2002

00:04:11.100 --> 00:04:14.190
and 2008, and the Visionary
Woman Award

00:04:14.190 --> 00:04:19.270
