eye-catching cartoons,

00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:35.340
and they included <i>One Nation
Under Surveillance </i>in 2005,

00:04:35.340 --> 00:04:40.120
and <i>Abortion Cartoons
on Demand </i>in 1992.

00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:42.680
She's also drawn cartoons
for <i>Ms. Magazine,</i>

00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:45.330
<i>Organic Gardening </i>,
and other publications.

00:04:45.330 --> 00:04:49.430
Her work has been exhibited
widely in group and solo shows.

00:04:49.430 --> 00:04:54.050
She launched "The Family
Tree," which is a comic strip

00:04:54.050 --> 00:04:55.970
that was syndicated and distributed

00:04:55.970 --> 00:05:01.430
by <i>United Media </i>in 2007
and ended it in 2011.

00:05:01.430 --> 00:05:07.570
Ann Telnaes, on the right,
creates animated editorial cartoons

00:05:07.570 --> 00:05:09.460
and a blog of print cartoons.

00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:13.240
Ann made gifs and sketches
for the <i>Washington Post </i>.

00:05:13.240 --> 00:05:17.860
In 2001 she became the second
woman to win the Pulitzer Prize

00:05:17.860 --> 00:05:21.360
for her political cartoons,
and they focused

00:05:21.360 --> 00:05:24.150
on the presidential
election of 2000.

00:05:24.150 --> 00:05:28.080
Other notable awards she has
received are the Clifford K.

00:05:28.080 --> 00:05:31.760
and James T. Berryman Award from
the National Press Foundation

00:05:31.760 --> 00:05:34.410
in 2003 and 2006.

00:05:34.410 --> 00:05:38.330
And in 2011 she was a finalist

00:05:38.330 --> 00:05:40.930
for the Herblock Prize
in Editorial Cartooning.

00:05:40.930 --> 00:05:46.980
In 1997 she also won a National
Headliners Award and other awards.

00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:50.130
She has served as the Vice
President of the Association

00:05:50.130 --> 00:05:53.060
of American Editorial
Cartoonists and is a member

00:05:53.060 --> 00:05:56.630
of the Cartoonists Rights
Network International.

00:05:56.630 --> 00:06:00.090
Her cartoons have been exhibited
nationally and internationally,

00:06:00.090 --> 00:06:04.560
including a solo exhibit
here at the Library in 2004.

00:06:04.560 --> 00:06:06.990
She has published two
collections of her bold,

00:06:06.990 --> 00:06:09.610
streamlined cartoon drawings

00:06:09.610 --> 00:06:15.230
in <i>Humor's Edge </i>which was a
companion volume to her exhibition,

00:06:15.230 --> 00:06:21.180
and <i>Dick </i>in 2006 which
revolved around cartoons

00:06:21.180 --> 00:06:24.730
of then Vice President Dick Cheney.

00:06:24.730 --> 00:06:30.920
Beginning in 2002 Ann contributed
to the daily comic "Six Chicks"

00:06:30.920 --> 00:06:35.260
for several years and to the online
publication <i>Women's eNews </i>from

00:06:35.260 --> 00:06:37.750
2002 to 2009.

00:06:37.750 --> 00:06:41.270
Much more could be said about both
of these wonderful cartoonists,

00:06:41.270 --> 00:06:45.510
but I would like to ask you to
welcome them to our program today.

00:06:45.510 --> 00:06:53.240
[ Applause ]

00:06:53.240 --> 00:06:57.480
All right, just -- I'm
going to ask Signe to begin

00:06:57.480 --> 00:07:02.320
by sharing her reactions to
the <i>Charlie Hebdo </i>tragedy,

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:09.250
and how she framed her thought
process in responded to it, first.

00:07:09.250 --> 00:07:10.880
Thank you.

00:07:10.880 --> 00:07:12.180
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson:
Thank you, Martha.

00:07:12.180 --> 00:07:16.430
When we got started on
this, planning this event,

00:07:16.430 --> 00:07:19.310
it was long before <i>Charlie Hebdo </i>.

00:07:19.310 --> 00:07:25.850
It was long before the more recent
controversies, and we were sort

00:07:25.850 --> 00:07:31.970
of wondering what the focus
would be, just free speech."

00:07:31.970 --> 00:07:38.340
And I regret to say that tragedy
has really become the centerpiece

00:07:38.340 --> 00:07:43.400 position:56%
of what most cartoonists are
talking and arguing about right now.

00:07:43.400 --> 00:07:52.680 position:56%
And just to be clear, my position is
that cartoonists don't kill people.

00:07:52.680 --> 00:07:56.610
Cartoons can't kill people.

00:07:56.610 --> 00:08:03.130 position:56%
Humorless, religious fanatics
generally do, or more often they do.

00:08:03.130 --> 00:08:08.760
A cartoon, a little
cartoon, a drawing on paper,

00:08:08.760 --> 00:08:12.520
pixels on a screen, cannot
stone anyone to death,

00:08:12.520 --> 00:08:17.260
it cannot sever a head, it
cannot send anyone to jail.

00:08:17.260 --> 00:08:21.720
And so the proportionality of what
we're talking about, a cartoon,

00:08:21.720 --> 00:08:27.460 position:56%
the drawing of a cartoon, and the
results that happened on January 7th

00:08:27.460 --> 00:08:31.040
in Paris are just so
disproportionate

00:08:31.040 --> 00:08:37.360
that it's almost hard to even
talk about it as well, you know,

00:08:37.360 --> 00:08:40.230
one thing equals the other.

00:08:40.230 --> 00:08:47.200 position:56%
But my interest in this goes back
to the Danish cartoons which started

00:08:47.200 --> 00:08:52.660
in 2005, and erupted in 2006
after several months of ginning

00:08:52.660 --> 00:08:56.300
up controversy about them.

00:08:56.300 --> 00:09:04.030
And I learned then that it's
really not about the image

00:09:04.030 --> 00:09:08.050
of Mohammad being prohibited
from being -- from drawing.

00:09:08.050 --> 00:09:12.460
And that's what I'd like to talk
about today, is the use of symbols

00:09:12.460 --> 00:09:17.460
and how we come to
focus on one thing.

00:09:17.460 --> 00:09:22.200
But, in reality, for at
least me as a cartoonist,

00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:24.030
it's been quite different.

00:09:24.030 --> 00:09:26.600
This, of course, this is
grabbed off the Internet,

00:09:26.600 --> 00:09:30.800
so I'm sorry the resolution
isn't good enough for you

00:09:30.800 --> 00:09:35.040
to be really shocked and
appalled that I am showing them.

00:09:35.040 --> 00:09:40.620
And this is a collection of the
Danish cartoons with the most,

00:09:40.620 --> 00:09:44.240
the one that caused
the most controversy

00:09:44.240 --> 00:09:47.300
up on the top with the turban.

00:09:47.300 --> 00:09:55.510
When that happened, it took a
while for the controversy to bubble

00:09:55.510 --> 00:09:58.880
over from Europe to
the United States.

00:09:58.880 --> 00:10:03.030
And nobody really knew that --
what it was all about, that this --

00:10:03.030 --> 00:10:05.040
that drawing Mohammad
was even a problem.

00:10:05.040 --> 00:10:10.220
One of the first papers
to publish the image

00:10:10.220 --> 00:10:14.730
in the United States was the
<i>Austin Statesman American </i>,

00:10:14.730 --> 00:10:16.820
which did it too early.

00:10:16.820 --> 00:10:20.980
No one knew that it was -- that
this was a prohibited image,

00:10:20.980 --> 00:10:24.420
and they got no reaction.

00:10:24.420 --> 00:10:30.010
People didn't know they were
supposed to be afraid and appalled.

00:10:30.010 --> 00:10:37.270
But shortly thereafter, it really
hit the fan and there were only

00:10:37.270 --> 00:10:44.200
about five other papers in the
country that managed to put

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:47.110
in a news item in the paper.

00:10:47.110 --> 00:10:49.450
And one of them was the
<i>Philadelphia Enquirer </i>.

00:10:49.450 --> 00:10:53.910
I word at the <i>Daily News </i>at
the time, and our paper did not.

00:10:53.910 --> 00:11:00.660
The <i>Enquirer </i>put one in one of
the interior pages in a little box

00:11:00.660 --> 00:11:06.200
with an explanation and --
just to alert its readers,

00:11:06.200 --> 00:11:08.570
this is what we're talking about.

00:11:08.570 --> 00:11:10.000
There were protests.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:17.740 position:56%
There were many follow-ups, meetings
with people who were unhappy.

00:11:17.740 --> 00:11:20.050
But what it did was
start a conversation

00:11:20.050 --> 00:11:21.900
in the city of Philadelphia.

00:11:21.900 --> 00:11:26.920
And right now we have a very
strong interfaith movement that,

00:11:26.920 --> 00:11:29.460
because it brought people
together to actually talk

00:11:29.460 --> 00:11:33.370
about these things
across religious lines.

00:11:33.370 --> 00:11:39.520
My editor, when I said, ooh,
I want to draw Mohammad, said,

00:11:39.520 --> 00:11:42.520
mm, not so sure about that.

00:11:42.520 --> 00:11:46.660
And he backed me up on many,
many other controversies.

00:11:46.660 --> 00:11:52.060
So I stewed for a couple of days
to figure out how I could do it.

00:11:52.060 --> 00:11:55.350
And I did this cartoon
-- "The Big Fat Book

00:11:55.350 --> 00:11:57.510
of Offensive Religious Cartoons."

00:11:57.510 --> 00:12:00.160
[ Laughter ]

00:12:00.160 --> 00:12:03.780
That's Mohammad, third
from the right [laughter].

00:12:03.780 --> 00:12:07.830
This cartoon has been reprinted
widely and was just sent

00:12:07.830 --> 00:12:09.990
around the world again via Twitter

00:12:09.990 --> 00:12:14.960
after <i>Charlie Hebdo</i>
, with no controversy.

00:12:14.960 --> 00:12:18.700
And the reason is that
Mohammad is cheerful,

00:12:18.700 --> 00:12:21.640
happy, and one of the guys.

00:12:21.640 --> 00:12:25.800
He's not portrayed negatively.

00:12:25.800 --> 00:12:28.880
And this is the point
I want to make.

00:12:28.880 --> 00:12:31.380
That it isn't about
drawing Mohammad.

00:12:31.380 --> 00:12:34.000
It's how Mohammad is drawn.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:39.180
And so it's a political, it's
the politics; it's not the image.

00:12:39.180 --> 00:12:43.020
And I have had this experience
in other cartoons as well.

00:12:43.020 --> 00:12:44.640
Oh, oops [laughter].

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:48.510
Wait, this isn't a
gay wedding, is it?

00:12:48.510 --> 00:12:55.040
[ Laughter ]

00:12:55.040 --> 00:13:01.880
Well, about half my audience like
this cartoon a lot [laughter].

00:13:01.880 --> 00:13:04.980
About half my audience said,

00:13:04.980 --> 00:13:09.840
"One should not be putting
a prophet in the newspaper."

00:13:09.840 --> 00:13:14.510
And then my Jewish readers said,
"How dare you put leavened bread.

00:13:14.510 --> 00:13:18.050
[ Laughter ]

00:13:18.050 --> 00:13:21.200
"That was a sedar dinner."

00:13:21.200 --> 00:13:24.030
I can't please everyone
all the time.

00:13:24.030 --> 00:13:26.200
I said, "That was my
artistic license.

00:13:26.200 --> 00:13:28.400
Have you ever tried to
draw matzo [laughter]?"

00:13:28.400 --> 00:13:34.900
So, again -- but I've
done cartoons --

00:13:34.900 --> 00:13:37.330
I did one with the Pope's
coming to Philadelphia.

00:13:37.330 --> 00:13:38.970
I want you all not to be there.

00:13:38.970 --> 00:13:42.120
There's no room in
Philadelphia next September.

00:13:42.120 --> 00:13:47.960
But the Archbishop liked it so
much, he sent it to the Vatican.

00:13:47.960 --> 00:13:53.030
It's like, okay, you can't do it
sometimes, you can do it others.

00:13:53.030 --> 00:13:58.310
And this -- we're covering the
major religions I've pissed off

00:13:58.310 --> 00:13:59.610
over my career.

00:13:59.610 --> 00:14:05.390
This was a tiny little illustration
in 1992 that went with a letter

00:14:05.390 --> 00:14:10.720
about Arab attacks on Israelis.

00:14:10.720 --> 00:14:12.940
It appeared on our Letters Page.

00:14:12.940 --> 00:14:16.020
Next day it was in birdcages.

00:14:16.020 --> 00:14:18.870
No one commented on it.

00:14:18.870 --> 00:14:22.330
About three months
later, this was 1992,

00:14:22.330 --> 00:14:24.570
a woman named Lynn
Yeakel was running

00:14:24.570 --> 00:14:28.600
against Arlen Specter,
our incumbent Senator.

00:14:28.600 --> 00:14:30.120
And she was gaining on him.

00:14:30.120 --> 00:14:34.850 position:56%
It was the Year of the Woman,
Clinton was running, and Spector all

00:14:34.850 --> 00:14:37.310
of a sudden's camp
got a little nervous.

00:14:37.310 --> 00:14:40.560
So they started a whispering
campaign about her,

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:42.830
saying that she was anti-Semitic

00:14:42.830 --> 00:14:45.520
for the most minor
infraction you can imagine.

00:14:45.520 --> 00:14:50.680
It was -- it didn't even involve
her, but somebody at her church,

00:14:50.680 --> 00:14:53.500
a thousand-member church.

00:14:53.500 --> 00:14:57.520
So there were letters to
the editor about that.

00:14:57.520 --> 00:15:04.810
And just by happenstance I drew
this with Lynn Yeakel being asked

00:15:04.810 --> 00:15:08.200
to prove that she is
not anti-Semitic.

00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:14.170
I was eviscerated for
this tiny little cartoon.

00:15:14.170 --> 00:15:18.810
People called, they wrote, people
came into the office and suggested

00:15:18.810 --> 00:15:26.250
to my editors that I find
other employment, that I was --

00:15:26.250 --> 00:15:33.700
called in letters "feminism's
own Goebbels," et cetera.

00:15:34.770 --> 00:15:36.100
There was a little blowback.

00:15:36.100 --> 00:15:38.600
Let's just put it that
way [laughter].

00:15:38.600 --> 00:15:44.290
But the argument was I should not
use the Star of David in a cartoon.

00:15:44.290 --> 00:15:47.920
However, this was okay.

00:15:47.920 --> 00:15:49.680
This was not.

00:15:49.680 --> 00:15:52.000
And it goes back to my points

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:57.640
on the other prophets
that we have looked at.

00:15:57.640 --> 00:16:01.150
It's not the symbol, it's
not the prophet itself.

00:16:01.150 --> 00:16:03.360
It's the politics behind it.

00:16:03.360 --> 00:16:07.450
And every group holds
certain things sacred.

00:16:07.450 --> 00:16:11.940 position:56%
The question in front of us is
whether we can let each group decide

00:16:11.940 --> 00:16:14.940
for everyone else what is sacred.

00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:18.730
And if we do, we will
not be drawing cartoons.

00:16:18.730 --> 00:16:22.480
So that's -- I turn
it over now to Ann

00:16:22.480 --> 00:16:24.740
to continue our --
do I have one more?

00:16:24.740 --> 00:16:26.040
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:16:26.040 --> 00:16:27.340
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: Oh, yes.

00:16:27.340 --> 00:16:32.510 position:56%
Just a small historical [laughter]
-- It was an early style [laughter].

00:16:32.510 --> 00:16:35.760
It was my 1876 style.

