And having been a woman that worked,
you know, in private businesses,

00:57:13.970 --> 00:57:17.410
and I just thought
you guys are crazy.

00:57:17.410 --> 00:57:18.990
Of course there's still
sexual harassment

00:57:18.990 --> 00:57:20.470
and of course we still
have to deal with it.

00:57:20.470 --> 00:57:21.770
So that's when I decided

00:57:21.770 --> 00:57:25.200
to put together a portfolio
and send it out.

00:57:25.200 --> 00:57:27.820
And I knew nothing about what I
was doing, which is really good

00:57:27.820 --> 00:57:29.760
because ignorance is
bliss [laughter].

00:57:29.760 --> 00:57:34.230
So -- and that's how I
got into the business.

00:57:34.230 --> 00:57:35.530
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson:
Just one other thing

00:57:35.530 --> 00:57:39.140
about women not going
into cartooning.

00:57:39.140 --> 00:57:43.210
I actually do think that there
is a difference between --

00:57:43.210 --> 00:57:46.860
generally speaking,
it's a huge spectrum,

00:57:46.860 --> 00:57:53.600
but women take things more
personally, generally, not,

00:57:53.600 --> 00:57:57.340
you know, on average, I'm
not making huge stereotypes.

00:57:57.340 --> 00:58:00.630
And there're clearly
exceptions to all rules.

00:58:00.630 --> 00:58:04.470
But, you know, Steve and
others in this room are --

00:58:04.470 --> 00:58:09.400
have gone to AAEC conventions,
our cartooning convention.

00:58:09.400 --> 00:58:12.330
It's oh, yeah, I really -- I got,

00:58:12.330 --> 00:58:14.590
I got a lot of reaction
out of that one.

00:58:14.590 --> 00:58:16.980
Oh, yeah. They really
went after me on that one.

00:58:16.980 --> 00:58:22.950 position:56%
You know? And that's not generally
the reaction that I hear from women.

00:58:22.950 --> 00:58:25.000
It's like, oh, my god [laughter].

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:30.340
They didn't like the color I did on
that woman's dress in my cartoon.

00:58:30.340 --> 00:58:31.940
No. I'm not saying that.

00:58:31.940 --> 00:58:33.240
I didn't say it [laughter].

00:58:33.240 --> 00:58:35.490
Erase the tape [laughter].

00:58:35.490 --> 00:58:42.370
But it is -- it's -- I'll quit
before I really bury myself, yeah.

00:58:42.370 --> 00:58:43.830
Okay, fine.

00:58:43.830 --> 00:58:47.440
But I do think that that's
a little bit of an issue.

00:58:48.640 --> 00:58:49.940
&gt;&gt; Ann Telnaes: Are we going on?

00:58:49.940 --> 00:58:51.240
Next question [laughter].

00:58:51.240 --> 00:58:52.540 position:56%
&gt;&gt; What about recording [inaudible]?

00:58:52.540 --> 00:58:53.840
&gt;&gt; Ann Telnaes: Yeah.

00:58:53.840 --> 00:58:58.510
&gt;&gt; So one of the things that I
read in Gary Trudeau's thing,

00:58:58.510 --> 00:59:00.810
and I read your response
to the blog here,

00:59:00.810 --> 00:59:03.980
was to talk a little bit
about responsibility.

00:59:03.980 --> 00:59:05.970
And you used that word which
I thought was going to be one

00:59:05.970 --> 00:59:07.560
of your words that you brought up.

00:59:07.560 --> 00:59:10.930
But my question is, is
there a limit to satire?

00:59:10.930 --> 00:59:15.160
Is there -- are there things
that are not satirical and then

00:59:15.160 --> 00:59:19.190
for our paper problems
or some other ways of --

00:59:19.190 --> 00:59:21.320
how would you guys define that?

00:59:21.320 --> 00:59:24.040
&gt;&gt; Ann Telnaes: Limits in satire?

00:59:24.040 --> 00:59:25.340
&gt;&gt; Are there?

00:59:25.340 --> 00:59:26.640
&gt;&gt; Ann Telnaes: Well,
that's really interesting.

00:59:26.640 --> 00:59:27.940
&gt;&gt; Because you were
pretty black and white

00:59:27.940 --> 00:59:29.240
like there is like no red lines.

00:59:29.240 --> 00:59:30.540
&gt;&gt; Ann Telnaes: Right.

00:59:30.540 --> 00:59:31.840
&gt;&gt; There can't be any.

00:59:31.840 --> 00:59:33.140 position:56%
I have to be able to say everything.

00:59:33.140 --> 00:59:34.440 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Ann Telnaes: Well, you know, it's
funny, it's funny you should ask

00:59:34.440 --> 00:59:36.000
that because I would
encourage everyone to go

00:59:36.000 --> 00:59:40.800
to the C-SPAN archives and
pull up Hustler v Falwell.

00:59:40.800 --> 00:59:43.720
It's really interesting
because they actually talk

00:59:43.720 --> 00:59:47.050
about are their limits in satire.

00:59:47.050 --> 00:59:50.900
And they actually use Gary
Trudeau as an example.

00:59:50.900 --> 00:59:54.140
They compare him to
what Falwell does --

00:59:54.140 --> 01:00:00.300
I mean to what Larry
Flint does in <i>Hustler </i>.

01:00:00.300 --> 01:00:05.360 position:56%
You know, his cartoons blasting H.W.
Bush about his manhood in a box?

01:00:05.360 --> 01:00:06.660
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: Yeah.

01:00:06.660 --> 01:00:07.960
&gt;&gt; Ann Telnaes: Yeah.

01:00:07.960 --> 01:00:12.860
And compare what Larry
Flint did in that Campari ad

01:00:12.860 --> 01:00:17.590
to what Gary Trudeau does in his
cartoons about George W. Bush.

01:00:17.590 --> 01:00:21.020
And, actually, it sounded like
the court came to the conclusion

01:00:21.020 --> 01:00:24.620
that in America -- now we're
talking about America here --

01:00:24.620 --> 01:00:29.860
the First Amendment, your Freedom
of Speech, you cannot limit that.

01:00:29.860 --> 01:00:32.120
Libel is something different, okay?

01:00:32.120 --> 01:00:33.430
That's something completely
different.

01:00:33.430 --> 01:00:35.530
And that's what the court
was trying to decide.

01:00:35.530 --> 01:00:37.620
But when it comes to satire,

01:00:37.620 --> 01:00:42.550
the word they used
was you -- what is it?

01:00:42.550 --> 01:00:44.860
You cause personal
harm or something?

01:00:44.860 --> 01:00:46.160
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson:
Distress, emotional distress.

01:00:46.160 --> 01:00:47.460
&gt;&gt; Ann Telnaes: Distress,
emotional distress,

01:00:47.460 --> 01:00:51.320
which basically means
you're hurting my feelings.

01:00:51.320 --> 01:00:53.130
And is there a limit there?

01:00:53.130 --> 01:00:55.910
And the court came to the
conclusion that is not a limit.

01:00:55.910 --> 01:00:58.850
It cannot be because
then you start --

01:00:58.850 --> 01:01:01.360
then it's like where is that line?

01:01:01.360 --> 01:01:02.770
Who's deciding that line?

01:01:02.770 --> 01:01:04.560
And if you -- and I encourage you.

01:01:04.560 --> 01:01:06.440
Go back and read that Campari ad.

01:01:06.440 --> 01:01:07.850
It's disgusting.

01:01:07.850 --> 01:01:09.830
It is just disgusting.

01:01:09.830 --> 01:01:13.930
And the court upheld it.

01:01:13.930 --> 01:01:16.600
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: That would
be the liberal William Rehnquist

01:01:16.600 --> 01:01:18.400
Supreme Court.

01:01:18.400 --> 01:01:21.040
[ Laughter ]

01:01:21.040 --> 01:01:22.340
&gt;&gt; Can I ask a question?

01:01:22.340 --> 01:01:23.640
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: Yeah.

01:01:23.640 --> 01:01:24.940
&gt;&gt; So to clarify.

01:01:24.940 --> 01:01:26.360
When you say that the
Campari ad was disgusting,

01:01:26.360 --> 01:01:29.470
I believe you're saying that's
something you would not have been

01:01:29.470 --> 01:01:30.770
involved with.

01:01:30.770 --> 01:01:33.280
You would not draw or -- I have
no idea what was in this ad.

01:01:33.280 --> 01:01:34.990
But that's something
you wouldn't do.

01:01:34.990 --> 01:01:39.890
So, if we're talking about the
limits of satire, you're saying,

01:01:39.890 --> 01:01:44.080 position:56%
and I agree with you there should
be no governmental limits on satire,

01:01:44.080 --> 01:01:47.950
but you as the individual
cartoonist draw your own limits

01:01:47.950 --> 01:01:50.200
on what you think is satirical

01:01:50.200 --> 01:01:53.380
versus what you think is people
are disgusting or something else.

01:01:53.380 --> 01:01:54.850
&gt;&gt; Ann Telnaes: Well, we
are professionals, you know.

01:01:54.850 --> 01:01:56.150
We do know what we're doing.

01:01:56.150 --> 01:01:58.410
I think that's why we always get
so pissed off when government tries

01:01:58.410 --> 01:02:00.180
to tell us what to
do with our bodies.

01:02:00.180 --> 01:02:01.900
We're, you know, we're adults.

01:02:01.900 --> 01:02:03.440
We can decide ourselves.

01:02:03.440 --> 01:02:05.190 position:56%
And it's the same thing with satire.

01:02:05.190 --> 01:02:07.530
You know, I -- the
thing that I want --

01:02:07.530 --> 01:02:11.210
I do not want the tools
being limited to me

01:02:11.210 --> 01:02:16.110
if I decide an image needs to be
used because what I believe is

01:02:16.110 --> 01:02:18.940
so strong about the
subject matter that I need

01:02:18.940 --> 01:02:21.140
to do something that's
going to get your attention.

01:02:21.140 --> 01:02:22.990 position:56%
It doesn't mean I'm going to use it.

01:02:22.990 --> 01:02:25.480
But I'm just saying, is I
don't want to see people limit

01:02:25.480 --> 01:02:29.610
that because I think it's
-- I know this is a cliche.

01:02:29.610 --> 01:02:31.940
It's a slippery slope if
you start doing that because

01:02:31.940 --> 01:02:35.540
if you start telling people I don't
like that, I don't like that --

01:02:35.540 --> 01:02:37.310
there's a lot of stuff I
don't like that's going

01:02:37.310 --> 01:02:39.010
on in this world, you know?

01:02:39.010 --> 01:02:40.860
And if I wanted to
start killing people

01:02:40.860 --> 01:02:42.420
over it then you'd have a problem.

01:02:42.420 --> 01:02:45.200
But -- that the problem is,

01:02:45.200 --> 01:02:49.510
is what people think is
and isn't acceptable.

01:02:49.510 --> 01:02:52.470
So, I don't know where
I'm going with that.

01:02:52.470 --> 01:02:54.450
But go ahead [laughter].

01:02:54.450 --> 01:02:57.090
&gt;&gt; Martha H. Kennedy: Well, one
thing I thought was interesting

01:02:57.090 --> 01:03:02.090
in the pieces, in response to
Gary Trudeau, was that a number

01:03:02.090 --> 01:03:06.050
of cartoonists actually said
they had personal limits

01:03:06.050 --> 01:03:10.140
and they've talked about
what they would not choose

01:03:10.140 --> 01:03:12.580
to show in their cartoons.

01:03:12.580 --> 01:03:15.910
And, anyway, that's just a point
that I thought [inaudible].

01:03:15.910 --> 01:03:17.300
&gt;&gt; Ann Telnaes: But the point is
nobody's telling them what their

01:03:17.300 --> 01:03:18.600
limits are.

01:03:18.600 --> 01:03:19.900
&gt;&gt; Martha H. Kennedy: No,
what their limits are.

01:03:19.900 --> 01:03:21.200
&gt;&gt; Ann Telnaes: Yeah.

01:03:21.200 --> 01:03:22.500 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Have either of you drawn cartoons

01:03:22.500 --> 01:03:25.220
that you wish you hadn't drawn
[inaudible] and take back?

01:03:25.220 --> 01:03:28.510
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: Oh,
only about 40% of them.

01:03:28.510 --> 01:03:32.120
[ Laughter ]

01:03:32.120 --> 01:03:33.420
No.

01:03:33.420 --> 01:03:35.480 position:56%
&gt;&gt; I mean at the point where you
maybe thought well maybe I did cross

01:03:35.480 --> 01:03:36.780
that line.

01:03:36.780 --> 01:03:38.100
Maybe I shouldn't have done that.

01:03:38.100 --> 01:03:41.580
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: There
are a couple that people took

01:03:41.580 --> 01:03:45.050
as way -- that I didn't mean them.

01:03:45.050 --> 01:03:49.250
It wasn't that the point,
my point was so extreme,

01:03:49.250 --> 01:03:53.430
but I was -- it was a bad cartoon.

01:03:53.430 --> 01:03:58.300 position:56%
If I didn't get my point across and
somebody felt that it was, you know,

01:03:58.300 --> 01:04:01.590
that it was saying something
I didn't mean to be saying,

01:04:01.590 --> 01:04:06.190 position:56%
that's not a good cartoon, and I
wished that I'd done it differently,

01:04:06.190 --> 01:04:07.820
especially ones that people --

01:04:07.820 --> 01:04:15.760 position:56%
and one in particular I remember was
really taken wrong by an individual,

01:04:15.760 --> 01:04:18.470
and I didn't mean to
harm that person.

01:04:18.470 --> 01:04:22.530
I had meant it, actually,
in support.

01:04:22.530 --> 01:04:24.660
So that was my --

01:04:24.660 --> 01:04:26.160
&gt;&gt; Mistakes were made.

01:04:26.160 --> 01:04:27.820 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: Yes, my -- Yeah.

01:04:27.820 --> 01:04:29.120 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Ann Telnaes: Yeah, it's basically

01:04:29.120 --> 01:04:32.060
if your cartoon isn't
the way you expected,

01:04:32.060 --> 01:04:34.590
you want it to be, come across.

01:04:34.590 --> 01:04:37.080
But it's -- we take that
responsibility on ourselves.

01:04:37.080 --> 01:04:38.380
You know what I mean?

01:04:38.380 --> 01:04:40.290
We'll question ourself and go,
why didn't I do it a certain way?

01:04:40.290 --> 01:04:41.590
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: Right.

01:04:41.590 --> 01:04:42.890
&gt;&gt; Ann Telnaes: Or if you
release it on a certain day.

01:04:42.890 --> 01:04:44.690
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: Oh,
you're being such a woman.

01:04:44.690 --> 01:04:48.280
[ Laughter ]

01:04:48.280 --> 01:04:52.300 position:56%
&gt;&gt; I was wondering whether the
reactions to your more controversial

01:04:52.300 --> 01:04:55.340
or politically incorrect
cartoons, if the reaction varies

01:04:55.340 --> 01:04:57.660
by age or generation at all.

01:04:57.660 --> 01:04:58.960
Like, in particular --

01:04:58.960 --> 01:05:00.260
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: Yes.

01:05:00.260 --> 01:05:01.560
&gt;&gt; -- do those under
30, do they take it

01:05:01.560 --> 01:05:02.860
about the same as everybody else?

01:05:02.860 --> 01:05:04.930
Or are they more accepting,
less accepting?

01:05:04.930 --> 01:05:07.190
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: Well, since we
don't have any newspaper readers

01:05:07.190 --> 01:05:08.490
under 30 --

01:05:08.490 --> 01:05:09.790
&gt;&gt; Right.

01:05:09.790 --> 01:05:11.820
&gt;&gt; [Clearing throat],
it's really hard to judge.

01:05:11.820 --> 01:05:13.570
But I think, yes, I
think you're right.

01:05:13.570 --> 01:05:17.140
And I think if you look at the
styles of younger cartoonists,

01:05:17.140 --> 01:05:20.410
they're quite different than
my style and Ann's style.

01:05:20.410 --> 01:05:23.430
So the next generation
of cartoonists is going

01:05:23.430 --> 01:05:26.380
to express things in
very different ways.

01:05:26.380 --> 01:05:29.320
So, yeah, I do think that
there's a difference.

01:05:32.250 --> 01:05:33.550
Yeah.

01:05:33.550 --> 01:05:39.160
&gt;&gt; Is there any cartoonist in the
United States who is as provocative

01:05:39.160 --> 01:05:41.730
as the cartoons [inaudible]?

01:05:41.730 --> 01:05:45.930
&gt;&gt; Ann Telnaes: Mr. Fish,
Dwayne Booth, great stuff.

01:05:45.930 --> 01:05:48.230
Go look at it [laughter].

01:05:50.040 --> 01:05:51.340
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: I --

01:05:51.340 --> 01:05:52.640
&gt;&gt; Another --

01:05:52.640 --> 01:05:53.940
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: One
more and then we wrap it up.

01:05:53.940 --> 01:05:55.240
Yeah.

01:05:55.240 --> 01:05:59.310
&gt;&gt; When we mention the limit
of satires, what is acceptable,

01:05:59.310 --> 01:06:02.010
[inaudible] do you mean
the powerful majority

01:06:02.010 --> 01:06:03.640
of the [inaudible] minority?

01:06:03.640 --> 01:06:05.880
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: Could
you repeat that, please?

01:06:05.880 --> 01:06:07.180
I'm not sure I --

01:06:07.180 --> 01:06:09.130
&gt;&gt; The limit of satire
in [inaudible] --

01:06:09.130 --> 01:06:10.990
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: Uh-huh.

01:06:10.990 --> 01:06:13.160
&gt;&gt; -- acceptable to you by
differing in the larger,

01:06:13.160 --> 01:06:17.740
powerful majority or
[inaudible] minority?

01:06:17.740 --> 01:06:19.880
&gt;&gt; Signe Wilkinson: Well, I
think this actually gets to some

01:06:19.880 --> 01:06:23.930
of the point that Gary
Trudeau was making.

01:06:23.930 --> 01:06:28.900 position:56%
He was saying that the cartoon -- as
I understand it, that the cartoons

01:06:28.900 --> 01:06:33.250
in <i>Charlie Hebdo </i>punched
down on people who did --

01:06:33.250 --> 01:06:35.580
who were not in the majority.

01:06:35.580 --> 01:06:37.960
And, therefore, it was a --

01:06:37.960 --> 01:06:43.820 position:56%
it's a cheap shot because they don't
have the same power as the majority,

01:06:43.820 --> 01:06:45.610
either the majority
of the cartoonists

01:06:45.610 --> 01:06:47.800
or the majority in the country.

01:06:47.800 --> 01:06:57.560
But -- and I think that
generally speaking cartoons are,

01:06:57.560 --> 01:07:02.440 position:56%
are seen as more powerful when
they're going after powerful people.

01:07:02.440 --> 01:07:09.250
I mean, they're the ones who are
setting the examples in the world.

01:07:09.250 --> 01:07:16.000
However, it's hard to say who's on
top and who's on bottom sometimes.

01:07:16.000 --> 01:07:19.720
I think in -- when you're
looking at, we'll just say Muslims

01:07:19.720 --> 01:07:28.500
at this point in France,
they're a minority.

01:07:28.500 --> 01:07:33.070
But in the headlines when
a group that identifies

01:07:33.070 --> 01:07:38.410
as a Muslim group takes over
an entire region of a country

01:07:38.410 --> 01:07:42.920
and starts executing people
and, you know, asking for --

01:07:42.920 --> 01:07:47.200
not asking, demanding forced
conversions, et cetera, et cetera,

01:07:47.200 --> 01:07:51.410
it's the same overall
group but I don't feel

01:07:51.410 --> 01:07:54.550
like I'm punching down
to criticize them.

01:07:54.550 --> 01:08:00.890
So I think it really depends on
what, you know, what the issue is

01:08:00.890 --> 01:08:03.290
and where it is you're focusing.

01:08:03.290 --> 01:08:09.660 position:56%
But it gets back to the whole global
that, you know, the global world.

01:08:09.660 --> 01:08:15.040
People may feel disenfranchised
one place and quite franchised

01:08:15.040 --> 01:08:20.160
in another place, even though the
large umbrella would put them --

01:08:20.160 --> 01:08:22.340
they would both be under
the same large umbrella.

01:08:22.340 --> 01:08:28.350
So that's, again, one of the
problems in sending cartoons

01:08:28.350 --> 01:08:31.070
across cultures and countries.

01:08:32.430 --> 01:08:33.730
&gt;&gt; Martha H. Kennedy: Thank you.

01:08:33.730 --> 01:08:36.620
I'd like thank both of
our cartoonists again,

01:08:36.620 --> 01:08:37.920
and I'd like to thank
all of you for coming.

